<TEXT>
a desert tank war with iraq 
would provide a formidable test of an american ground war strategy 
that relies on a combination of vietnamera weapons and costly 
ultramodern systems never tested in combat 
should the desert standoff come to blows us military planners 
believe the american forces would win but only after a bloody fight 
it is also a fight they would rather wage at night 
until iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait the us military had 
never trained with iraq as its mock opponent but the weapons and 
tactics of iraq would not be unfamiliar its tanks are sovietmade 
and it has adopted the soviet tactic of massing huge numbers of 
tanks and supporting them with heavy artillery 
weve trained since the beginning of the cold war for this 
fight an army source said recently the only difference now is 
wed fight it in the saudi arabia instead of germany against iraq 
and not the russians 
iraqs strengths are its sheer numbers roughly 5500 tanks 
its familiarity with the terrain and experience from eight years of 
war with iran 
the united states outnumbered on the ground is said to have 
superior missiles air power and groundlevel sighting guidance 
and weapons systems 
the troops and weapons that make up the united states tank war 
arsenal have been arriving gradually since the us deployment 
began three weeks ago but much of the force is now in place 
the armys heavy m1 tanks began arriving tuesday and are being 
sent into the northeastern desert where several antitank units 
already are in place 
in a tank war with iraq the united states would seek to counter 
iraqs greater numbers with a massive air assault first targeting 
iraqi groundtoair missile systems according to dozens of 
commanders pilots and tank crews interviewed over the past two 
weeks 
iraq has modern sovietmade antiaircraft systems but us 
planners are confident they could be significantly damaged by 
american british and saudi planes 
the next phase in the air according to the interviews would 
involve the air forces a10 tank killer jets and the premiere 
american antitank weapon the new ah64 apache attack helicopter 
the a10 flys as slowly as 100 knots carries missiles and a 
30mm sevenbarrel cannon it is vulnerable to enemy fire but has 
several redundant systems to keep it flying after hits and also a 
titanium tub around the cockpit to protect the pilot during what 
one a10 commander col sandy sharpe refers to as air to mud 
warfare 
the apache carries up to 16 hellfire laserguided missiles like 
its carrier untested in combat but said to be highly accurate it 
also has two 19rocket pods and an antitank gattling gun 
the hellfire will destroy any known armor in the world said 
lt col don vinson an apache pilot and commander 
apaches are considered an ideal tank killer at night when they 
can sit back well beyond iraqi range and fire missiles 
they cant see us but i can see and kill them said armt 
lt col dick cody 
army and marine cobras vietnamera choppers that have been 
refitted with new weapons and electronics also could be called 
into any large tank war cobras are armed with tow missiles and 
gattling guns 
the major cog in the ground strategy the 24th infantry 
mechanized division began rolling its m1 tanks northward into 
the desert on tuesday 
in an allout battle the untested m1s and their 105mm cannons 
would be riding into the desert accompanied by bradley armored 
infantry carriers which has a 25mm gun and slots through which 
passengers can fire their m16s 
despite their size an m1 weighs 60 tons the tanks can 
travel at speeds of up to 45 mph or more 
the other tanks in the us arsenal the m60as belonging to the 
7th marine expeditionary brigade and the m551 sheridans deployed 
with the 82nd airborne division both date back to vietman 
the sheridans which carry shillelagh missiles saw combat duty 
then and when dropped into panama during the december us 
invasion the m60s date back to vietnam but never have been 
tested in combat 
iraqs huge tank army is led by modern sovietmade t72s which 
are considered by many experts a rival to the ameican m1 
make no mistake about it theyve got more tanks than us and 
theyve got some damn good tanks a us tank commander said 
us military planners are counting on their superior air power 
the tripledigit heat and terrain of the saudi desert would be a 
factor in any tank fight 
there are some high dunes but for the most part it would be 
difficult for any great number of tanks to hide 
tow heaven responded one weapons specialist when asked about 
the desert well seem them coming for miles 
the ships carrying us tanks were asked to bring additional 
filters for the m1s which need to be cleaned frequently and 
higher viscosity oil was put on supply lists because of the heats 
wear and tear on the equipment 
it will make it a lot tougher out there in the heat said 
sgt ronald ruff of hinesville ga but when youre cleaning or 
changing a filter or something in combat you learn to speed up a 
little 
