<TEXT>
israel is trying to maintain a restrained 
stance on the persian gulf crisis despite growing fears its own 
interests will be undermined if iraqi leader saddam hussein is not 
toppled 
a lowkey posture is not easy for israel and strong rhetoric 
keeps cropping up from military analysts often voicing leaks from 
the government and from officials themselves sometimes followed 
by hasty reversals 
the dilemma for israel is that it is the united states 
bestarmed and closest ally in the middle east but has been 
sidelined in this crisis by political necessity 
washington does not want its friendship with the jewish state to 
undermine the coalition of moderate arab states it has brought 
together in response to saddams aug 2 lightning seizure of kuwait 
stuck on the sidelines israelis are increasingly uneasy that 
diplomatic efforts to end the crisis and political maneuvering by 
saddam will lead to a military stalemate 
there is concern building here that somehow saddam may get 
away with his aggression eytan gilboa a professor of 
international relations at hebrew university said tuesday that 
leaves us still facing his military machine 
a similar view was expressed by the hebrew daily yediot ahronot 
which said in an editorial that a diplomatic compromise for the 
kuwait crisis would mean that we would remain here alone with 
saddam and his mad ambitions only four minutes away from his 
missile launchers and chemical bombs 
saddam an implacable foe of israel has a millionman army and 
has threatened to turn his chemical weapons against the jewish 
state 
he also has championed the goal of palestinians to form an 
independent state in the israelioccupied west bank and gaza strip 
sparking prosaddam rallies in the territories and neighboring 
jordan 
fear of iraqs potential military menace prompted reserve army 
gen avigdor bengal a hero in the 1973 arabisraeli war to 
advise that the united states turn its tactical nuclear weapons 
against iraq 
bengal told israel radio i think the americans made a 
mistake by not acting quickly and taking chances those who 
want to take minimum risks could find themselves in a situation 
where they cannot act even though they are ready 
prime minister yitzhak shamir has tried to keep the lid on 
saying that israel has no intention of getting involved with iraq 
unless it is attacked 
he reacted angrily on tuesday to allegations in us 
publications that israel was using its alliance with president bush 
to warmonger 
who are we to push the biggest superpower in the world 
shamir told a parliament hearing we are not pushing the united 
states to any war 
still it was shamir himself who caused a storm last week when 
he hinted that a preemptive israeli strike against iraq was 
possible 
he told a gathering of american jewish donors that in the 
circumstances our major task is to prevent war or to preempt it 
and if heaven forbid these two fail and there is no alternative 
we have to win quickly and decisively 
under questioning from reporters shamir quickly qualified his 
statement and said israels aim was to prevent any military 
involvement of our country 
defense minister moshe arens too has retracted hawkish 
statements 
on monday arens told israel television that israel would not be 
pleased by a solution that left saddam in power on tuesday 
standing before two usmade f15 jets during an air base news 
conference he denied he called for saddams ouster 
were not involved in managing this crisis and were not 
setting the conditions for how to handle it arens said 
yet the question of whether israel is or should advise the 
united states to go to war is being widely discussed by israelis 
mordechai gur a former army chief of staff told state 
television tuesday that israeli officials should be careful of what 
they say because some americans consider their remarks provocative 
if we would not go to war let us not send other children to 
war and let us not bereave other families gur said its their 
right to try to end the crisis by political means 
the israeli government has already stated its own red lines 
for war a direct strike or entry by iraqi forces into neighboring 
jordan which serves as a buffer between israel and sadddams army 
israel americas largest aid recipient at 3 billion annually 
also made it clear that it is concerned with the advanced american 
weaponry being supplied to saudi arabia and other arab states 
confronting iraq 
israel is against the sale of arms to countries which refuse 
to enter the peace process with israel said a foreign ministry 
official who insisted on anonymity israel wants to remind the 
united states of the necessity of preserving a qualitative edge 
</TEXT>
