black american saint 
acting state supreme court justice phyllis gangeljacob on 
tuesday granted the request from the archdiocese of new york to 
exhume pierre toussaints body for identification by a pathologist 
and church officials 
it is rare that this court has an opportunity to participate 
in such a historic event if only tangentially the judge said 
church records show toussaint who died a free man in 1853 at 
87 was buried at old st patricks cathedral 
court papers referred to him as a model of charity who is 
considered the founder of catholic charities because he helped the 
needy for 66 years when no formal systems of assistance existed 
gangeljacob said that toussaint had lived a long and 
apparently virtuous life giving money to the poor and nursing 
the ill during the yellow fever plagues that swept new york city 
before antibiotics 
in those times the only consolation may have been the miracles 
of faith and trust the judge said her voice breaking 
indeed for the thousands of victims of the scourge of aids 
alzheimers disease melanoma and other currently incurable 
diseases the same may be true today 
monsignor robert oconnell said the church is investigating two 
miracles attributed to toussaint a haitian mans claim he was 
cured of lung and stomach cancer by praying to toussaint and a 
miami womans claim he cured her breast cancer 
the congregation for the causes of saints in rome which is 
responsible for canonization will hold investigations and a 
hearing that could take years oconnell said 
toussaint was born into slavery in haiti in 1766 at 21 he was 
brought to new york by a frenchman and his family after the 
frenchmans death the masters family fell into poverty toussaint 
secretly supported them for 20 years until the widow remarried and 
repaid him by arranging for his freedom 
</TEXT>
