<TEXT>
the traditional view that women who have given 
birth by caesarean section must always deliver that way is being 
challenged in a new survey 
the american college of obstetricians and gynecologists said it 
found in a survey of 2213 physicians that 63 percent of women who 
attempt vaginal delivery after a previous caesarean section 
succeed results of the study were released tuesday 
strides certainly have been made to persuade women and their 
doctors that vaginal deliveries are safe successful alternatives 
to repeat caesareans said dr mary jo osullivan secretary of the 
organization 
however osullivan said because about 42 percent of the 
patients surveyed chose to have another caesarean there is a 
need to further educate women about the benefits of vaginal 
deliveries 
osullivan associate chairwoman of obstetrics at the university 
of miami in florida said vaginal deliveries are less risky than 
caesarean sections mainly because the latter is a surgical 
procedure 
in addition she said vaginal births are less expensive and the 
patient spends less time in the hospital an average of 4334 and 
two or three days compared with 7186 and four or five days for a 
caesarean according to 1989 data from the health insurance 
association of america 
the rate of caesarean deliveries rose from 55 percent of all 
us births in 1970 to 247 percent in 1988 
but osullivan noted that the increase from 198687 and from 
198788 was 03 percent the smallest rise in five years 
