<TEXT>
an appeals court says the federal trade 
commission lacked authority to prohibit states from banning 
shopping center stores that combine optometric practice with 
eyeglass sales 
the us court of appeals for the district of columbia on 
tuesday ruled that the ftc had acted beyond its statutory 
authority in its march 1989 eyeglasses ii ruling last year 
an agency may not exercise authority over states as sovereigns 
unless that authority has been unambiguously granted to it 
circuit judge james buckley wrote in a ruling agreed to by chief 
judge patricia wald and circuit judge douglas h ginsburg 
ftc attorney lawrence demillewagman said the commission had not 
yet decided whether to appeal 
the ftcs ruling never took effect because the california state 
board of optometry and others sought and received a stay from the 
appellate court moments after the ruling would have become 
effective last sept 1 said california deputy attorney general 
thomas s lasar 
the states had imposed restrictions that the court said tended 
to discourage the commercial practice of optometry such as 
partnerships between optometrists and laymen use of trade names 
and chain operations combining the practice of optometry with the 
sale of eyeglasses in shopping centers in favor of traditional 
optometric practice typified by sole practitioners operating in 
professional office buildings under their own names 
the ftc began investigating the restrictions in the mid1970s 
and in findings published in 1980 indicated that these 
restrictions resulted in higher prices and reduced the quality of 
eye care available to the public buckleys opinion noted 
nine years later the ftc adopted eyeglasses ii even though 
ftc chairman daniel oliver voted against it based on principles 
of federalism and his view that the ftc was without authority to 
promulgate it 
</TEXT>
