<TEXT>
secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar 
known more for discretion than dynamism suddenly stepped forward 
this week and seized world headlines with a bid to personally 
mediate the persian gulf crisis 
the un chief often goes weeks on end without attracting much 
notice outside the glass facade of un headquarters relying on 
lowkeyed diplomacy to solve conflicts 
then came his weekend announcement that he will meet iraqi 
foreign minister tariq aziz in amman jordan on thursday to try to 
bring an end to iraqs occupation of kuwait and free all the 
foreign hostages caught by the aug 2 invasion 
he followed up with a rare news conference monday and capped 
that with live interviews with us television networks on the 
evening newscasts 
diplomats and un officials pondered this unprecedented 
outburst by an official who is fond of the french saying the 
melody makes the song not a loud voice 
up to now his style has been a study in understatement as he 
labored quietly to bring recalcitrant enemies into peace 
negotiations 
he was perus ambassador to the united nations in 197175 and 
special un representative to cyprus from 197577 in 1979 he 
became undersecretarygeneral for special political affairs 
un insiders say that as special representative to afghanistan 
in 1981 perez de cuellar sketched the framework for the superpower 
settlement that led to soviet withdrawal from afghanistan 
completed last year 
perez de cuellar spent many hours with the iraqi and iranian 
foreign ministers in 1988 to solidify the unmandated ceasefire 
in their war the relationship he established with aziz may prove 
useful on thursday 
another long conflict the guerrilla war in western sahara 
appears headed to an end soon after years of unobtrusive un 
mediation 
the new cooperation between the superpowers is the key to the 
united nations recent successes perez de cuellar owes thanks to 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev for taking the first steps to 
end the cold war 
for years east and west tested each other in proxy wars among 
their client states and used their veto power in the united nations 
to block effective diplomacy 
during the lean years from 1982 to 1986 perez de cuellar 
could only lay the groundwork for future successes brian urquhart 
the former chief un peacekeeping offical said in a 1988 
newspaper interview 
in perez de cuellars first year as secretarygeneral argentina 
and britain fought their 74day falkland islands war 
while that conflict was still going on israel invaded lebanon 
defied security council demands for a ceasefire and withdrawal 
and bypassed the 7000member un peacekeeping force in southern 
lebanon 
the years 1982 to 1986 were awful nothing was going right 
urquhart said but he used that time to build up a negotiating 
position in afghanistan iran iraq and all those places when the 
climate changed he was in a position to go forward quickly 
un insiders also credit perez de cuellar with recruiting a 
small but highly effective circle of key aides to draft un 
policy in cambodia latin america the middle east afghanistan and 
other trouble spots 
he doesnt upstage them by launching unexpected initiatives 
which is why his move this week caught so many un observers off 
guard 
iraq had dug in its heels rejecting security council 
denunciations and calling the world body the pawn of the united 
states the un chief was away on a south american tour 
many wondered why he didnt rush back to headquarters during the 
crisis 
after the security council voted saturday to allow military 
force to enforce the economic blockade on iraq perez de cuellar 
suddenly announced his peace initiative and returned to new york 
while supporting security council resolutions demanding 
immediate iraqi withdrawal he carefully drew a distinction between 
his role and that of the council 
the security council composed of 15 nations cannot mediate in 
a crisis only the secretarygeneral can do that he said 
perez de cuellar was not in his usual seat at the council table 
when it passed five resolutions faulting iraq for its actions now 
he could offer himself as an honest broker to iraq 
some officials and diplomats believe perez de cuellars new 
higher profile paves the way for his successor to be a more active 
international mediator after his term ends in 1992 perez de 
cuellar has said he will not stand for reelection 
