convictions by referring the case to the court of appeal but the 
verdicts were in 1988 
lets hope this time it works for us said mcilkennys wife 
kate who lives in birmingham 
i hope that the court will deal with the case speedily in 
order that this great scandal may be brought to an end as soon as 
possible said chris mullin a member of parliament who wrote a 
book about the case 
mullin of the opposition labor party claims he has met ira 
members who admitted carrying out the birmingham attack 
the bombings were the deadliest ever by the ira in england in 
its campaign against british rule in northern ireland 
the birmingham six case is the last of three major trials of 
suspected ira guerrillas from the 1970s to be returned to the 
appeal courts following vigorous public campaigns claiming their 
innocence 
three men and a woman convicted of killing six people in 
bombings in guildford and woolwich in 1975 were freed by the court 
of appeal in october six other people convicted in a related case 
of operating an ira bomb factory are awaiting an appeal hearing 
after waddington announced in june that the convictions were 
unsafe 
in march waddington asked the devon and cornwall constabulary 
to investigate certain undisclosed points raised by defense 
attorneys 
as part of that investigation the police carried out 
electrostatic deposition tests on records of the west midlands 
police force whose detectives investigated the birmingham bombings 
a year ago west midlands chief constable geoffrey dear 
suspended two detectives and reassigned 53 members of the serious 
crime squad after electrostatic deposition tests indicated that 
records had been falsified in cases going back to 1986 
the appeal by the guildford and woolwich defendants also hinged 
on questions about police documentation prosecutors admitted that 
officers had lied about the timing of a statement by one of the 
defendants 
supporters of the birmingham six argue that their confessions 
contradict one another that police tampered with logs to make 
statements appear consistent that forensic evidence was flawed and 
that there was no witness who testified to seeing any of the men in 
the two pubs 
their cause had been taken up by amnesty international the 
irish government and leading irish and british political and 
clerical figures 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

