prime minister toshiki kaifu said today that japan 
will not transport soldiers or weapons to aid the international 
force in the persian gulf but he pledged money medical personnel 
and nonmilitary supplies 
japans assistance package unveiled in a nationally televised 
speech appeared to fall short of the aid level sought by the 
united states which has deployed tens of thousands of troops to 
saudi arabia since the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait 
although japan quickly joined the trade embargo against iraq 
further response was slowed by debate over what action was 
permissible under japans postworld war ii constitution which 
bars the use of force in settling international disputes 
under the plan kaifu said japan will use civilian airplanes and 
ships to transport food water and medical supplies to the gulf 
japan also promised to send about 100 medical personnel 
turkey egypt and jordan were singled out for substantial 
economic assistance according to a copy of the package tens of 
thousands of foreigners fleeing kuwait and iraq have made their way 
to jordan 
