<TEXT>
sales of new homes fell 23 percent in july 
giving up half of their gain the previous month the government 
said today in a report showing continuing weakness in the housing 
industry 
the commerce department said new home sales totaled a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 548000 after advancing a revised 47 
percent in june the department originally reported june sales up 8 
percent 
the continuing weakness was further illustrated by the 
departments downward revision in the may sales figure as well 
last months reported 23 percent gain was reduced to just 06 
percent today 
until may new home sales had declined for five straight months 
for the first seven months of the year they have fallen 124 
percent below the pace of 1989 
the department also said inventories of new homes showed a 
78month backlog at the july sales pace it had been 77 months in 
june 
analysts have attributed the weakness in the industry to high 
interest rates consumer caution because of adverse economic news 
and a glutted market 
the national association of realtors reported on monday that 
sales of existing homes which represent about 80 percent of the 
housing market rose 33 percent in july after advancing 09 
percent in june 
but the june advance had been the first in seven months and 
analysts predicted more declines because of rising mortgage rates 
resulting from the mideast crisis 
after peaking at 1067 percent in march fixedrate 30year 
mortgages fell to 998 percent by the end of july according to the 
federal home loan mortgage corp but by last friday rates had 
moved up to 1029 percent 
commerce said the median price of a new home fell 47 percent in 
july to 121000 the median price means half of the homes cost 
more and half less the median price of an existing home that month 
was 98400 according to the realtors 
sales in the northeast which have been sluggish for more than a 
year fell 101 percent to an annual rate of 80000 units the 
department also revised the june increase downward from 369 
percent to 253 percent 
sales also fell in the west down 49 percent to 135000 units 
while they were unchanged at 237000 units in the south 
sales rose 21 percent to 96000 units in the midwest 
