mohawk negotiators met with government officials 
today in an effort to end a standoff between troops and indians 
after the army announced it was bringing in hundreds more soldiers 
to dismantle barricades 
quebec native affairs minister john ciaccia said the talks were 
under way at the request of the mohawks and that he had briefed 
quebec premier robert bourassa tuesday night 
ciaccia said he wasnt calling the talks to end the 7weekold 
standoff formal negotiations and the armys intention to 
dismantle the barricades had not changed 
negotiators declined to comment as they entered a hotel room in 
dorval 
canadian fighter jets on tuesday swooped over the oka area near 
montreal where heavily armed mohawks have dug in at a road 
barricade in a dispute over a planned golf course addition that 
they say would encroach on ancestral soil 
about a dozen miles away just south of montreal mohawks backing 
the oka protest have barricaded a commuter bridge in sympathy 
the mercier bridge blockade has angered many people who use the 
bridge to commute to montreal and about 500 people stoned mohawk 
families leaving the adjacent kahnawake reservation on tuesday 
some injuries were reported 
brig gen armand roy tactical commander of the soldiers moving 
in on the two sets of barricades told a news conference late 
tuesday that military operations will cease only when the armed 
warriors lay down their weapons and surrender without conditions 
roy added that he has ordered his soldiers to move closer to 
indian positions in preparation for a move to dismantle the mohawk 
barricades at the kahnawake and oka reservations 
oka is 18 miles west of montreal the kahawake reservation lies 
between the mercier bridge and suburban towns that depend on the 
bridge to cross the st lawrence river to get to montreal 
early today the army announced that 675 more men 136 wheeled 
vehicles and 50 tracked vehicles would be deployed to the outskirts 
of the kahnawake reservation before tuesday about 2500 combat 
soldiers were positioned outside both reservations 
the number of indian fighters is believed to be in the hundreds 
the army says mohawks at the barricades have at least 170 automatic 
weapons and an intricate network of trenches bunkers and strong 
points 
lt gen kent foster said tuesday that soldiers would use three 
unarmed 42ton leopard tanks equipped with a bulldozer front to 
remove the barriers he would not say when dismantling would begin 
prime minister brian mulroney blamed mohawk negotiators for the 
crisis 
he went on national tv on tuesday and challenged mohawks to take 
down the barricades themselves before the army does he said the 
federal and quebec governments had dealt with the land dispute in 
good faith but mohawk bargainers advanced unrealistic 
conditions and then demanded acceptance 
we cannot overlook the illegal activities of an extremist 
minority mulroney said referring to the mohawks warrior 
contingent 
mohawk negotiator billy two rivers said one more day of talks 
should break the impasse and open mercier bridge and the roads 
leading to it 
we are in a process of achieving through negotiation what the 
army was mandated to do by force he said after tuesdays 
session were positive that in the next 24 hours things can be 
resolved 
but mulroney said he consulted quebec authorities and that a 
settlement doesnt appear to be within reach 
foster said there were plans to evacuate people from military 
zones if necessary and that those that live in surrounding areas 
will be told to stay in their basements 
many local residents have complained bitterly about the 
barricading of the mercier bridge which has led to lengthy 
commuting detours and meant lost business 
