aug 25 
the registerguard eugene ore on natural resources 
new evidence that a substance extracted from yew trees can be 
used as an effective treatment for certain types of cancer 
transforms a lowgrade natural resource into a potentially 
important one it also teaches important lessons todays weed tree 
may be tomorrows miracle and what once was wasted may soon be 
developed as a valuable resource 
the pacific yew grows in small quantities over a broad range in 
the northwest its uses are ancient but limited the longbows that 
defended england against viking raids were made of yew but it has 
never been a major commercial species today yew wood is still 
used for bows as well as canoe paddles fence posts and decorative 
veneers the market is so limited however that loggers usually 
ignore yew in favor of douglas fir hemlock and other trees better 
suited as saw timber 
that may change with the discovery that taxol a compound found 
in the bark and other parts of trees of the yew or taxus genus 
holds promise as a treatment for ovarian cancer ovarian cancer 
kills 12400 women a year in the united states efforts to 
synthesize taxol have so far been unsuccessful 
the potential emergence of what one dendrology book describes as 
a small bushy untidy tree as a treatment against a common type of 
cancer underscores the fact that there are no unimportant species 
judging a tree or a bird or a flower to be of no significance says 
more about the limits of human understanding than about the species 
in question every form of life has value of some kind but the 
true worth of many has yet to be discovered 
</TEXT>
