<TEXT>
some 1990 us coin proof sets that sell for 
11 are worth more than 100 times that because of a missing mint 
mark on a penny according to dealers 
the penny in the 3555 sets is missing the s all proof coins 
normally bear that makes them unusual and valuable to collectors 
the sets of highly polished coins were struck and issued before 
the error was discovered us mint spokeswoman hamilton dix 
confirmed tuesday 
i stuck my neck out when these things showed up and predicted 
that by the end of the decade these things will be worth 10000 
said alan herbert who broke news of the error in the aug 7 
edition of numismatic news newspaper of iola wis 
we have talked with a collector who had ordered five sets from 
the mint and all five of those sets were missing the mint mark 
said beth deischler editor of coin world newspaper in sidney ohio 
at that time he wasnt considering selling at any price 
the errors are a prize because there are so few of them 
ms deischler said 
coin dealer harry forman of suburban cheltenham paid 1400 each 
last week for four sets and is now offering 1700 per set 
the proof coins are made by using polished blanks and dies the 
flat surfaces are mirrorlike and the relief portions look frosted 
the 11 fivecoin set contains a penny nickel dime quarter and 
half dollar a sixcoin prestige set adds a proof dollar and sells 
for 46 
proof coins are struck at the san francisco mint and thus should 
bear an s under the date dies for striking the coins are made 
at the philadelphia mint the philadelphia mint puts no mark on 
pennies it strikes but they all go into general circulation 
were investigating to find out exactly what happened miss 
dix said we are taking steps to ensure this does not happen 
again 
similar errors were made on proof nickels in 1971 and proof 
dimes in 1968 1970 1975 and 1983 herbert said 
