<TEXT>
the federal trade commission warned consumers 
wednesday to be leery of energy saving schemes saying the public 
can be duped by getrich proposals and devices claiming to save 
gasoline 
unscrupulous individuals often attempt to exploit situations 
like the present one by taking advantage of consumers said ftc 
chairman janet steiger 
the ftc was joined in the warning by the national association of 
attorneys general 
attorney general mary sue terry of virginia president of the 
association noted that with the labor day weekend ahead 
consumers should stay away from devices or fuel additives that 
claim to significantly increase fuel mileage 
rising energy prices and concern about future oil supplies is 
likely to unleash an array of fraudulent schemes ranging from the 
sale of phony gassaving devices to oil and gas investment frauds 
the ftc said 
among the things the ftc warned consumers about were 
phony investment schemes involving oil or gas partnerships 
gold and silver mining or oil drilling that promise much higher 
rates of return than normally might be expected 
when wall street is jittery all kinds of investment scams 
appear warned the ftc 
energy saving devices such as surge suppressors or furnace 
duty cyclers that may be costly without providing significant 
energy savings 
home improvement scams including the sale of improper solar 
energy systems storm windows siding or insulation in some cases 
the promised energy savings may never be achieved the agency said 
if the savings claims appear unrealistic they probably are 
said the ftc 
gadgets or gasoline additives that are supposed to improve 
automobile mileage none of these products has been found to 
significantly increase fuel economy said the ftc 
the agency suggested the best ways to save gasoline is to 
inflate tires to their proper pressure remove excess weight from 
the cars trunk and make sure the car is properly tuned it also 
advised against use of high octane gasoline unless it is 
recommended in the automobile manuel higher octane gasoline is 
more expensive and often does not improve car performance 
the ftc also warned the public to be aware of telemarketing 
techniques that offer great bargains because of the oil crisis 
and reminded that calls to 900 numbers often cost from 2 to 
45 a minute 
telemarketing techniques themselves are not deceptive indeed 
many reputable companies use them but in the hands of unscrupulous 
individuals they can hurt consumers said the ftc 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

