the state of florida and the army have 
agreed to work together to find civilian jobs for soldiers put out 
of work by the end of the cold war 
despite the current deployment of thousands of us soldiers in 
the mideast the 764000 active duty forces will be pared down 
during the next few years and could see annual cuts of 35000 
according to michael stone secretary of the army 
it is what becomes of those 35000 soldiers per year that 
were talking about today stone told gov bob martinez and the 
cabinet on tuesday 
the project involves finding soldiers jobs as teachers 
truckers health care workers and law enforcement officers the 
state plans to send out brochures and offer a hotline number 
promoting job counseling services for outofwork soldiers 
florida will become the first state in our country to 
implement programs that will help military personnel with 
education training and job placement services education 
commissioner betty castor said 
although stone said it was not inappropriate to make plans for 
the future of the army with the unfolding persian gulf crisis he 
said personnel cutbacks would be put on hold until the 
confrontation is resolved 
but he thanked the state for its willingness to be out front 
in such an important project 
the army has not yet worked out similar agreements with other 
