<TEXT>
the government on wednesday ordered an appeals 
court to reopen the cases of six irishmen convicted of murdering 21 
people in a pair of ira pub bombings in 1974 saying police may 
have tampered with evidence 
though doubts were raised only about evidence against one 
defendant home secretary david waddington ordered the court of 
appeal to review all six cases 
it is good news but im keeping my feet firmly on the 
ground said hugh callaghan one of the socalled birmingham six 
who have maintained their innocence for 16 years 
their convictions were affirmed by the court of appeal in 1988 
the explosions in two pubs in birmingham on nov 21 1974 were 
the deadliest attack ever mounted in england by the outlawed irish 
republican army in its campaign against british rule in northern 
ireland the explosions killed 21 people and injured 162 
scientific tests of police notes of an interview with convict 
richard mcilkenny indicated that some pages were written at 
different times the home office said 
waddington said the interview with mcilkenny implicated one 
other defendant but fairness required a review of all six cases 
its very very difficult to disentangle the significance of 
evidence like this for the case of one defendant as compared with 
its significance for the case of the other defendants waddington 
said in an interview with bbc radio 
chris mullin a member of parliament who wrote a book arguing 
the innocence of the six said it was likely that much additional 
new evidence would be presented to the court 
for the first time i detect that there is a will on the part 
of many of those in authority to bring this great scandal to an end 
once and for all said mullin a member of the opposition labor 
party its casting a blight upon our whole legal system not only 
at home but around the world 
irish prime minister charles haughey said the new appeal was 
very good news relations between britain and ireland have been 
strained by the birmingham six case and others in britain involving 
ira suspects 
five of the six men were arrested a few hours after the 
bombings as they were about to board a ferry to belfast northern 
ireland for the funeral of an ira member 
mcilkenny callaghan johnny walker patrick hill gerry hunter 
and billy power were convicted of murder in 1975 and sentenced to 
life in prison 
they were refused the right to appeal in 1976 and failed in a 
1977 lawsuit alleging that they were assaulted by investigating 
officers a decade later the government acknowledged doubts about 
their convictions by referring the case to the court of appeal 
which affirmed the convictions 
the birmingham six case is the last of three major trials of 
suspected ira guerrillas from the 1970s to be returned to the 
appellate courts following vigorous public campaigns proclaiming 
the defendants innocence 
three men and a woman convicted of killing six people in 
bombings in guildford and woolwich in 1975 were freed by the court 
of appeal in october six other people convicted in a related case 
of operating an ira bomb factory are awaiting an appeal hearing 
after waddington announced in june that the convictions were 
unsafe 
in march waddington asked the devon and cornwall constabulary 
to investigate certain undisclosed points raised by attorneys for 
the birmingham six 
devon and cornwall police conducted electrostatic deposition 
tests on records of the west midlands police force whose 
detectives investigated the birmingham bombings the test can 
determine when a document was written and whether any alterations 
have been made to it 
a year ago west midlands chief constable geoffrey dear 
suspended two detectives and reassigned 53 members of the serious 
crime squad after the tests indicated that records had been 
falsified in cases going back to 1986 
supporters of the birmingham six argue that their confessions 
were contradictory that police tampered with logs to make 
statements appear consistent that forensic evidence was flawed and 
that no witness testified to seeing any of the men in the two pubs 
