news programs can claim exemption from federal equal opportunity 
commonly known as equal time rules if candidates are the 
subjects of bona fide newscasts documentaries or other types of 
legitimate news events 
but because jackson will be an interviewer and not an 
interviewee a station probably could not claim such an exemption 
said milton gross chief of the federal communications commissions 
fairnesspolitical programming branch 
gross said he gave such an opinion informally to someone who 
called him on behalf of the nbcowned station in washington 
wrctv which broadcasts inside edition he would not identify 
the caller 
the subject of the news would be exempt but not the 
interviewer gross said 
he added that inside edition had not sought an equal time 
exemption as a news program as have some other shows such as 
hard copy and entertainment tonight 
gross based his opinion on a supreme court ruling involving a 
california newscaster who also was a political candidate the 
newscaster had argued that the equal time rules were depriving him 
of his livelihood but the court said station employees could not 
claim the exemption gross said 
jacksons appearance on inside edition would not be exempt 
if the supreme courts decision were applicable gross said 
the fcc official said he did not know if the equal time rules 
would apply to a washington station that used portions of jacksons 
inside edition appearance on its regularly scheduled news 
programs 
