<TEXT>
president rodrigo borja halfway through 
his term has not convinced the people he can solve ecuadors 
economic problems and faces the added burden of a hostile congress 
annual inflation of 50 percent spurs discontent and many 
analysts say borjas last two years may be a time of paralyzing 
political confrontation his democratic left party lost its 
congressional majority in june 
i greatly fear the new legislature will devote itself to 
waging war on the government which in turn will defend itself like 
a wounded animal with every weapon available alejandro carrion 
a respected columnnist wrote in the magazine vistaso 
all is not bleak however ecuador exports oil and higher 
prices resulting from the middle east crisis could produce an 
economic bonanza for the government said fernando santos 
energy minister under borjas rightwing predecessor leon febres 
cordero 
oil is a government monopoly and provides nearly 50 percent of 
public revenue in ecuador a small andean nation of 10 million 
people borja based this years budget on an average price of 15 a 
barrel but fluctuating prices since iraq occupied kuwait on aug 2 
have reached more than twice that 
borja took office in august 1988 three months after winning a 
runoff with populist abdala bucaram febres cordero could not run 
again because presidents are allowed only one term in ecuador 
febres cordero left a stagnant economy and record annual 
inflation of 88 percent for most of the 1980s inflation had 
averaged less than 30 percent 
the new president pledged to cut inflation in half before the 
end of his first year but the figure dropped only to 547 percent 
this year he renewed the promise to halve inflation but the 
annual rate continues to run above 50 percent independent 
economists predict it will level out at 40 percent by years end 
experts blame borjas restrictive spending policies for slow 
economic growth the central bank says the economy grew only 04 
percent in 1989 
his government rejected a shock anttinflation program of 
the type favored by the international monetary fund preferring 
gradual measures like small currency devaluations and energy price 
increases introduced weekly 
analysts say the repeated increases in gasoline and electricity 
prices contributed to the governing democratic lefts crushing 
defeat in the june 17 congressional elections 
it retained only 14 of its 30 seats and lost the majority it had 
forged in the onehouse legislature through an alliance with a 
minor party 
among the parties gaining ground was febres corderos 
conservative social christian party which increased its membership 
in the 72seat chamber from seven to 16 
bucarams ecuadorean roldosista party won 13 seats an increase 
of five and the socialist party a marxist group doubled its 
presence to eight 
bucaram and febres cordero have promised borja will face tough 
going in the new congress which convened aug 10 and immediately 
demanded that seven of his 12 cabinet members resign 
among those on the list was the agriculture minister blamed by 
the opposition for recurring food shortages and the education 
minister accused of embezzling funds from a literacy campaign 
andres vallejo a former interior minister appointed central 
bank president in july is another target the opposition claims he 
persecuted critics while in charge of the interior ministry which 
controls the police 
by recent ecuadorean standards borjas first two years were 
tranquil 
febres cordero his fierytempered predecessor had to battle a 
hostile congress with a leftist majority led by borjas party 
he put down two attempted coups in 1986 and a year later was 
kidnapped by air force paratroopers and forced to pardon the air 
force commander who led the coup attempts 
congress then tried to impeach him without success 
