<TEXT>
educators previously afraid of sounding heartless now openly 
warn of a possible taxpayer backlash as regular education budgets 
are pinched by mounting special education costs forcing tax 
increases 
cases like this bring about a schizophrenia our hearts tell 
us to do something but our common sense tells us that there are 
limits said thomas a shannon executive director of the 
national school boards association which filed a brief in support 
of the rochester school district 
according to a cost analysis done for congress last april by the 
national association of state directors of special education total 
education spending in new york state rose 901 percent from 
198088 but special education spending increased by 1864 percent 
in 1980 special education accounted for 11 percent of all 
expenditures in 1988 it had increased to 166 percent 
other states surveyed reported similar figures in florida 
total education spending rose 1254 percent compared with 2102 
percent for handicapped youngsters in 1980 special education 
amounted to 81 percent of all education spending but rose to 112 
percent eight years later 
and new costs are just around the corner 
in 1986 congress passed a law entitling handicapped 
preschoolers as young as 3 to public education starting in 1991 
any state that doesnt provide such services risks losing federal 
special ed funds 
special educators accuse the federal government of being quick 
to heap evergreater responsibilities on school districts but slow 
to fund them 
the 1975 act envisioned that the federal government would pay 40 
percent of the total bill but washington never provided more than 
14 percent and has contributed less than 10 percent throughout the 
1980s 
the law also called on state mental health social service 
vocational rehabilitation and education departments to cooperate in 
funding and providing special education services 
a few states notably maryland and illinois are pooling 
resources from various state agencies to help fund services for 
handicapped kids but such cooperation remains rare said william 
schipper executive director of the national association of state 
directors of special education 
adding to the fiscal strain on local districts the current 
trend of deinstitutionalization has placed thousands of youngsters 
once consigned to state mental hospitals into the care of public 
