<TEXT>
the bells that toll to open american schools 
this month also proclaim the arrival of something new and 
troublesome the first big wave of children exposed to crack in 
the womb 
many of these kids now entering preschool and kindergarten 
classes have special needs and most schools are not ready to 
deal with them 
with few exceptions i dont think that schools are prepared 
to handle this issue im thinking programwise as well as 
financially said samuel sava head of the national association 
of elementary school principals 
children who were exposed in utero to crack other forms of 
cocaine and other drugs can exhibit a wide range of symptoms 
including tremors hyperactivity listlessness and the inability to 
organize their thinking 
many do not fit any special education or disability category 
and health professionals fear teachers are not being equipped to 
handle their neurological emotional and learning problems 
all agree that their exposure to drugs coupled with unsettled 
home lives mean that these children need help 
if solid earlychildhood education is not provided these 
children may not survive said joan altshuler an education 
diagnostician with the hillsborough county fla schools which is 
working to teach these children 
each year an estimated 375000 american children are born 
having been exposed to cocaine and other drugs while in the womb 
of those about 200000 are believed to have traces of crack in 
their system at birth 
no one knows exactly how many of these kids are about to enter 
school when the incoming kindergarten and preschool class was 
born the numbers of crack babies were smaller the epidemic was 
in its early stages 
but educators say it is clear that the number of crack kids is 
about to take a quantum leap and those numbers will escalate in 
coming years 
we are just now beginning to recognize how we must work with 
these children said sava noting that studies show drugexposed 
youngsters may soon comprise 40 percent to 60 percent of innercity 
school populations 
some districts are preparing educators in fulton county ga 
spent the summer providing teacher training workshops focused on 
these children 
ohio has formed a special task force on drugexposed infants 
with the goal of completing a resource center by 1992 los angeles 
has a pioneering special education program in place for 
drugexposed kids 
hillsborough county intends to educate these kids in regular 
classes kindergarten teachers will attend workshops to help them 
identify drugexposed youngsters and to learn how best to teach 
them 
teachers are taught to use masking tape to create work spaces on 
tables glue footprints on the floor to show line up areas and 
tack a calendar at a childs eyelevel so children can know what 
activities to expect 
altshuler said most drugexposed youngsters are not well 
organized and can be easily confused by having too many things 
going on at once they require structure to overcome the chaotic 
and transient nature of the drug environment in which many still 
live 
care also must be taken not to overstimulate them because they 
might misbehave or be too overwhelmed to focus in on any one 
task 
teachers are asked not to put too many things on the walls to 
limit the number of books and games piled on shelves and to have 
activities planned for virtually every minute of the day 
these children cant wait they need to know what to do it 
may be get a book and look at it and then well go to lunch 
they cant have any lags in their day teachers have to be on at 
all times altshuler said 
she acknowledged theres nothing earthshaking about these 
suggestions and that the techniques would not adversely affect 
other students 
philosophically we want these children to stay in regular 
education were not talking about children with tremendous 
physical neurological and mental disabilities she said 
sam is one of those children he has eye problems and trouble 
retaining what he has learned one day he will count the next day 
he will forget how 
he is 5 years old and he is one of seven students in the 
graduating class at the operation par child development and family 
guidance center in st petersburg sam is energetic he loves the 
center and he responds eagerly to the staffs quick hugs and ready 
smiles 
at first its difficult to tell that sam and his 5yearold 
friend tom who has difficulty controlling his emotions have 
developmental problems that will require them to spend some time in 
special education after graduation 
many of the kids have learned the alphabet and numbers through 
music sam and tom bounce right along to the reggae beat of the 
blaring music as teacher alice bradley sings out the numbers 
printed on cards they hold 
these children arent different than any other children 
except for the mood swings said teacher eula hollaway 
the center opened in june 1988 mainly to provide free child 
care for women seeking help with drug addiction but it soon became 
a vital part of these childrens lives and program director 
shirley davis worries about their future once they enter public 
schools 
florida has the highest dropout rate in the country as it is 
were going to send them off to school and im not sure were going 
to put them in places where people will really attend to the 
problems that these kids have and that they will really work on 
these children she said 
teachers may hear the words cocaine baby and they have this 
preconceived notion that these children cannot learn and therefore 
we dont teach them 
sometimes i get really upset when educators come to us and 
say what do they look like davis said when you see these 
children they look like everybody they are our children we 
want them to look like quasimodo so we can label them and put them 
over in the corner 
operation par president shirley coletti who founded the program 
20 years ago when she learned one of her four teenagers was 
experimenting with drugs says its important to talk about 
hopefulness instead of hopelessness 
there is reason to believe that in time whatever disabilities 
these children have will subside she said 
i think its going to require a tremendous amount of training 
on the part of the prekindergarten kindergarten and firstgrade 
teachers we must have research dollars to do some longerterm 
studies otherwise i think youre going to see a lot of 
terribly discouraged teachers she said 
money is a major concern the florida department of human 
resources estimates that it would cost 40000 per child per year 
to provide all the services each child needs up to school age and 
no one has estimated the cost once the children are in school 
altshuler stressed that the government and other policymakers 
must take steps to reduce classroom size and provide other 
assistance for those teachers and educators who gripe about the 
responsibilities she has a simple message 
its your job to teach the child its your job to accept 
them the positives and negatives and concentrate on the strengths 
of the child and go from there we cant put everybody in special 
education so we better find what were going to do in our 
classrooms 
