<TEXT>
the government said today its main forecasting 
gauge of future economic activity was flat in july indicating 
widespread weakness in the us economy even before the persian 
gulf crisis increased the chances of a recession 
the commerce department said the lack of any change in the index 
of leading economic indicators followed revised gains of 01 
percent in june and 06 percent in may 
but analysts said they expected a steep drop in august because 
of the oil price spike and consumer jitters spurred by fears of war 
in the middle east following the aug2 iraqi invasion of kuwait 
typically three consecutive declines in the index are viewed as 
a fairly reliable although not infallible signal that the economy 
is headed for a recession 
following iraqs invasion many economists believe a recession 
is looming as an already sluggish us economy falls victim to 
rising inflation and consumer worries about a possible war 
in another economic report today the commerce department said 
sales of new homes fell 23 percent in july giving up half of 
their gain the previous month the government said new home sales 
totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 548000 after 
advancing a revised 47 percent in june 
while the leading index normally forecasts economic activity six 
to nine months in advance some analysts believe the next recession 
may start sooner with the most pessimistic believing the country 
may already be in a downturn 
already the stock market one of the components which makes up 
the index has staged a sharp retreat and consumer confidence is on 
the skids 
initial reports from the university of michigan which 
measures consumer sentiment for commerce indicate that the 
consumers first reaction to the iraqi invasion was near panic 
according to economist mark m zandi of regional financial 
associates in west chester pa 
the sentiment index fell 15 points more than after the 1987 
stock market crash to a level consistent with previous 
recessions he said although sentiment has likely improved 
in recent days the risks of a consumer retrenchment are 
rising 
since consumer spending represents twothirds of the nations 
economic activity many analysts fear the persian gulf crisis could 
cause further retrenchment leading to a recession 
however after falling in may and june the consumer index rose 
slightly in july other positive contributors to the index were an 
increase in orders for new plants and equipment and an increase in 
the price of raw materials 
negative contributors were faster business delivery times a 
decline in the money supply a drop in manufacturers unfilled 
orders a shorter average workweek a drop in building permits an 
increase in weekly unemployment claims and a decline in the stock 
market 
one of the components orders for consumer goods was unchanged 
the various changes left the index at 1461 percent of its 1982 
base of 100 and up 14 percent from its level a year ago 
if a recession can be avoided through november the economic 
expansion already the nations longest in peacetime will have 
reached its eighth anniversary 
but it has been growing sluggishly for two years and some 
analysts contend that if the economy is not in a recession now it 
soon will be 
the us economy was stagnating well before the persian gulf 
crisis merrill lynch economists wrote in their weekly economic amp 
financial commentary they noted the economy grew at a meager 12 
percent annual rate in the second quarter and said thirdquarter 
indicators so far have been uniformly weak 
for july they said employment declined industrial 
production was flat retail sales did not keep pace with inflation 
and housing starts dropped to the lowest level since 1982 and 
that covered the period before the persian gulf crisis 
consumer spending represents twothirds of the nations economic 
activity and economists worry that a major cutback could halt 
economic growth altogether and even push the nation into recession 
even before the invasion many analysts were citing consumer 
concerns over rising interest rates a lack of job growth high 
levels of debt the savings and loan crisis and other adverse 
economic news 
consumer spending is only up about 1 percent year over year 
said merrill lynchs bruce steinberg that is typical of a 
recession 
since then numerous polls have shown consumers growing even 
more cautious just monday the new yorkbased conference board 
reported its survey of 5000 households nationwide showed 
confidence plummeted nearly 18 points to a sevenyear low of 838 
in august the index had remained virtually unchanged at 1017 in 
july 
a war situation causes consumer confidence to fall explained 
richard peach an economist with the mortgage bankers association 
people become unwilling to take on major responsibilities like 
buying a new house 
in addition the surge in oil prices forces individuals to spend 
more for gasoline and heating costs and leaves them with less 
discretionary income for such items as cars and refrigerators 
and with major sectors such as automobiles and housing already 
weak analysts say it would not take much of a shove to force the 
economy into a decline 
