toyota motor corp japans largest automobile 
manufacturer plans to triple the sales of its nonautomotive 
divisions by 1994 the company said wednesday 
executive vice president masami iwasaki made the disclosure at a 
news conference where he also reported toyotas consolidated profit 
had risen 274 percent in its latest fiscal year 
iwasaki said toyota will raise the output of its nonautomotive 
divisions from roughly 2 percent of its sales to 6 percent 
though small in percentage terms 6 percent of toyotas total 
domestic sales would be 4799 billion yen or 31 billion based 
on the companys latest annual sales figures 
in addition to cars toyota also produces industrial vehicles 
such as forklifts and shovel loaders builds homes and manufactures 
factory automation equipment 
toyota and other japanese automobile manufacturers have 
traditionally devoted a much smaller part of their operations to 
nonautomobile sectors than their european or american 
counterparts the move is thought to represent toyotas decision to 
begin diversifying away from automobiles as world demand for cars 
shrinks and competition intensifies 
it also comes at the same time that american auto makers have 
been selling off their nonautomobile subsidiaries 
iwasaki said toyota would revise its charter to permit the 
company to enter new fields such as aerospace medical equipment 
and ceramics but he said it expected greatest growth in housing 
industrial vehicles and factory automation 
the company also announced wednesday that its consolidated net 
profit rose 274 percent to 4413 billion yen or about 285 
billion in the fiscal year ended june 30 from 3463 billion yen a 
year earlier 
its pretax earnings were up 339 percent to 8378 billion yen 
or 55 billion from 6257 billion yen the previous year the 
consolidated statement includes 39 subsidiaries and related 
companies 
consolidated sales totaled 919 trillion yen or 600 billion 
up 146 percent from 802 trillion yen in sales last year 
the manufacturer said robust domestic sales coupled with 
moderate expansion in southeast asia and steady growth in north 
america underlined its strong showing 
unconsolidated exports fell 110 percent to 1608484 vehicles 
for the year while overseas production rose by 835 percent 
toyota said intensifying competition within japan an expected 
slowdown in growth of automobile demand in the united states plus 
any impact from the middle east crisis might make it more difficult 
to achieve similar results in the future 
nevertheless the car maker said it plans to increase vehicle 
sales within japan by 40 percent and exports by 76 percent during 
the next fiscal year 
