<DOCNO> AP900829-0237 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal deposit insurance corp said 
wednesday it has issued a ruling effectively barring 
statechartered savings and loan associations from withdrawing from 
the federal home loan bank system for at least 18 months 
the action eases concerns that the fdic might be on the verge of 
allowing a giant exodus of sampls from the system which would 
cripple the systems ability to finance the savings and loan 
bailout 
the action came on a request by the wauwatosa savings and loan 
association of wauwatosa wis which had asked if it could 
maintain its federal deposit insurance if it pulled out of the 
federal home loan bank of chicago 
in a statement the fdic said it could make no assurances at 
this time to wauwatosa that it would be able to retain its deposit 
insurance should it withdraw from membership in the federal home 
loan bank system 
because both banks and sampls depend on federal deposit insurance 
to operate the fdic decision effectively blocks any exodus by 
statechartered institutions out of the sampl system 
the fdic said its action which was taken at a closed board 
meeting on tuesday was based on recommendations made by the office 
of thrift supervision the agency which regulates the sampl industry 
the ots said that the withdrawal of sampls from the home loan bank 
system would pose safety and soundness concerns 
the fdic did agree to review the matter in 18 months it said 
that would give the ots time to draw up regulations clarifying the 
situation the ots is expected to propose a regulation that would 
require statechartered sampls to belong to the federal home loan 
bank system 
of the 2505 savings and loans still operating about half of 
them are federally chartered and the other half have state charters 
both state and federally chartered sampls were members of the 
federal savings and loan insurance corp the nowdefunct agency 
which provided insurance of up to 100000 per deposit at sampls 
the sampl bailout legislation passed by congress last year made it 
clear that federally chartered sampls must maintain their membership 
in the sampl system even though their insurance fund was being 
administered by the fdic however the legislation was less clear 
about the status of statechartered thrifts 
the home loan bank system is required to contribute up to 300 
million annually as its share of the sampl bailout a burden which 
some sampls have complained adds to their cost of operation and makes 
it difficult for them to compete with commercial banks 
however bush administration officials contended that if the 
fdic allowed statechartered sampls to leave it would make it 
difficult for the home loan bank system to come up with its 
required contribution to the bailout 
</TEXT>
