<TEXT>
five central american countries 
have asked mexico and venezuela for relief from the increase in oil 
prices prompted by the middle east crisis 
the military invasion of kuwait by iraq which deeply concerns 
our people will affect the world petroleum market and will bring 
inevitable political and economic consequences for central 
america president rafael leonardo callejas told the associated 
press 
meanwhile wednesday venezuela said it planned to increase oil 
production capacity and brazil said it would receive more oil from 
iran to make up for shortages due to the embargo on oil from iraq 
and occupied kuwait 
under the 10yearold san jose agreement five central american 
countries have been buying venezuelan and mexican oil for an 
average 17 a barrel paying 80 percent in cash mexico and 
venezuela allow the other 20 percent to be used as loans for 
development projects or to finance imports from venezuela and 
mexico 
under the proposal by honduras and four other nations the 
countries would pay 70 percent of their oil bills in cash as long 
as prices remain high callejas said the other 30 percent would be 
covered as credits for purchases of mexican or venezuelan goods and 
services or as loans for development projects 
the other four nations are el salvador costa rica nicaragua 
and guatemala the san jose agreement also covers belize panama 
jamaica the dominican republic and barbados 
meanwhile venezuela plans to increase its oil production 
capacity to 286 million barrels per day in 1990 a 60000barrel 
increase petroleos de venezuela said wednesday 
venezuela is actually pumping only about 2 million barrels daily 
