<TEXT>
the repaired and renamed ship that caused the 
countrys worst oil spill left san diego bay for sea trials 
wednesday after a multimilliondollar repair job to its mangled 
hull 
the rebuilt exxon mediterranean formerly named the exxon 
valdez got underway at 645 am as tugboats pulled the ship from 
a pier and guided it through the harbor 
there were no protesters trailing the ship as there were when 
the 32000ton tanker with its severely damaged hull was towed 
into harbor from alaska 13 months ago 
workers at national steel amp shipbuilding co replaced 3000 tons 
of steel in the mangled hull during the 11month 30 million 
repair job the 987footlong tanker was floated out of dry dock 
last month and underwent dock trials at a nassco pier 
the ship which was built at nassco and delivered to exxon in 
1986 will head for international waters about 100 miles from the 
san diego coast and some 25 miles past san clemente island said 
nassco spokesman fred hallett 
officials from nassco the coast guard and the american bureau 
of shipping will be aboard the ship during the sea trials which 
are expected to last between a week and 10 days exxon spokeswoman 
carrie chassin said wednesday 
all the structural work has been approved but this sea trial 
is to make sure everything is in perfect operating condition 
chassin said they will be testing all the systems of the ship 
the steering a comprehensive review until everyone is satisfied 
during sea trials the crew will run the tanker at full speed 
make maximum turns and test machinery and equipment hallett said 
typically when we repair a ship we dont put it through a 
shakedown hallett said but because of the extensive repairs 
and the problems it had exxon will put it through a shakedown as 
if it were a new ship 
exxon officials deny that the tankers renaming in july was 
related to the spill of nearly 11 million gallons of oil when the 
ship ran aground on alaskas prince william sound on march 24 1989 
officials say the tanker will transport crude in the 
mediterranean the vessel holds nearly 14 million barrels of 
crude and is too big for any us pacific ports when fully loaded 
exxon officials have said they also say tankers that big arent 
needed for west coast shipping routes because of declining 
production from alaskan oil fields 
