<DOCNO> AP900829-0249 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chicago board of trade should develop an 
electronic trading system create new products and attract new 
members and capital as it heads into the 21st century an report 
released wednesday said 
as the world continues to change and competition in our 
markets increases the chicago board of trade will face many new 
challenges and opportunities board of trade chairman william f 
oconnor said 
as an institution we must be prepared to act boldly to meet 
the changes headon he said 
the report was prepared by a task force headed by robert s 
hamada deputy dean of the university of chicago business school 
it said the board of trade must pursue a diverse set of new 
futures contracts to buy or sell everything from orange juice to 
wheat to securities at a specific date because of advantages in 
launching a product and intense competition 
the study said that despite the introduction of a number of new 
trading products in recent years 51 percent of the exchanges 
volume comes from treasury bond futures 
the study also concluded that paperless trading is essential to 
the future of pit trading and recommended pursuing new technology 
to that end 
the board of trade should use electronic systems that most 
closely duplicate the open outcry auction trading the study 
concluded the task force contended that the auction system adds to 
the liquidity of the market 
although the board of trade is negotiating with the rival 
chicago mercantile exchange to join in the globex trading system 
developed by the merc the task force said that should not 
interfere with experimentation with the aurora trading system being 
developed by the cbot 
the task force also recommended better incentive systems to 
attract members and capital to new products the study concluded 
that a mix of capital pools permits fee rebates and electronic 
trading systems should be developed and used to accomplish the goal 
the study also concluded that the current trading floor for 
financial futures is overcrowded and that the exchange should 
remedy the problem 
the report comes as the exchange battles some presentday 
problems the board of trade and the mercantile exchange received a 
black eye when an investigation into illegal trading activity 
resulted in the indictment of 48 people 
the exchange is also faced with a desire by regulators in 
washington to increase federal oversight of the commodities 
industry industry leaders say that could reduce the 
competitiveness of us futures market as foreign competition 
increases 
the task force recommended the exchange delegate authority to 
allow it to make quicker decisions the study said such a move 
would allow exchange leaders to focus on broad policy issues not 
operational details 
</TEXT>
