<TEXT>
the government decided wednesday to 
investigate whether some japanesemade electronic equipment are 
imported at less than fair value into the united states 
threatening the domestic industry 
the international trade commission ruled 40 that there is 
reasonable indication that imports of some electronic display 
screens used in computers and their subassemblies materially injure 
us industry 
the finding means the commerce department will conduct an 
antidumping investigation with hearings a preliminary decision is 
due dec 28 the itc said 
the procedure could result in import duties on the japanese 
products representing the margin of underpricing 
the equipment known as highinformation content displays 
display in color or blackandwhite text graphics or images the 
output of computers dataprocessing machines word processors 
television receivers and scientific instruments 
the commission took action in response to a petition filed by 
the advanced display manufacturers of america a trade group and 
its member companies it said the us industry makes the devices 
in beaverton ore waukegan ill milbury and northwood ohio 
and troy mich 
the announcement did not include data about the us market and 
the extent of import penetration which it said was confidential 
business information 
